{{Notability|Biography|date=December 2016}} '''Queva Griffin''' (born 10 August 1983<ref name="indo"/> - May 2003<ref name="marathon">{{cite news |title=This marathon's for Queva |work=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] |page=4 |date=27 October 2003 |url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A110373502/GPS?sid=wikipedia |first=Roughan |last=MacNamara |via=[[InfoTrac Newsstand]] |subscription=yes |accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>) was an [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] poet.<ref name="gem">{{cite news |title=What a little gem |work=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] |date=29 June 1998 |page=13 |via=[[InfoTrac Newsstand]] |url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A70280187/GPS?sid=wikipedia |subscription=yes |accessdate=12 December 2016 |first=Richie |last=Taylor}}</ref><ref name="IT"/><ref name="indo">{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/happy-returns-for-the-birthday-girl-26176978.html |first=Mary |last=Shanahan |date=11 August 1998 |accessdate=5 December 2016 |title=Happy returns for the birthday girl ... |work=[[Irish Independent]]}}</ref> A sufferer of [[Cystic fibrosis]], Griffin was a double organ recipient, the first person under-25 to survive a heart-lung double transplant.<ref name="OpUnit">{{cite web |accessdate=5 Dec 2016 |url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/IRELAND+TO+GET+VITAL+OP+UNIT.-a063617500 |via=[[The Free Library]] |publisher = The Mirror |date = 22 July 2000| author = Young, Caoimhe |title=Ireland To Get Vital Op Unit }}</ref> She published a book of poetry as a fundraiser for the costs associated with her illness.<ref name="marathon"/> She was named ''[[Young Person of the Year]]'' in 1998 for her courage during the transplant process.<ref name="IT">{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/taoiseach-praises-remarkable-people-at-award-ceremony-1.212729 |work=[[Irish Times]] |date=10 November 1998 |title=Taoiseach praises `remarkable people' at award ceremony |author = Pollack, Andy |accessdate=5 Dec 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/us-senator-scoops-award-for-brokering-north-deal-26167827.html | publisher = Independent News & Media | title = US senator scoops award for brokering North deal |author = Reid, Lorna | date = 10 November 1998 | quote = "''Dublin schoolgirl Queva Griffin (16) was named as the Young Irish Person of the Year''" |accessdate = 12 December 2016 }}</ref> She died in May 2003, after picking up an infection.<ref name="marathon"/>
