{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians --> | name = Sai Kham Leik | image = | caption = | background = non_performing_personnel | birth_place = Thenni Township, [[Shan State]], [[Burma]] | birth_name = | alias = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|4|27}} | origin = | instrument = | genre = [[Folk rock]] | occupation = [[Physician]], [[songwriter]] | years_active = 1969–present | label = | associated_acts = [[Sai Htee Saing]], The Wild Ones | website = }} {{Burmese name|Sai}}
'''Sai Kham Leik'''{{lang-my|စိုင်းခမ်းလိတ်}}), also known as Louis Kham is a successful and prolific Burmese [[songwriter]]. Said to be a physician by training he is an ethnic [[Shan people|Shan]] songwriter and has written more than 500 songs in [[Burmese language|Burmese]], 200 in [[Shan language|Shan]] and about 35 in English. His father, Kham Ka, was a noted poet and a former minister of [[Hsenwi]] Palace. He was born on 27 April 1949 in Hsenwi. He has three siblings. He married Dr. Nwe Nwe Tin in 1971 and has four children.. He taught [[anatomy]] at the [[University of Medicine, Mandalay]] from 1990 to .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2549%3Achiangmai-shans-to-celebrate-songwriters-60th-birthday-today&Itemid=301 |title=Chiangmai Shans to celebrate songwriter’s 60th birthday today |publisher=Shanland.org |date=2009-04-27 |accessdate=2013-08-20}}</ref> He is also a persistence promoter of Shan culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanland.org/index.php?view=article&catid=102%3Amailbox&id=2542%3Asai-kham-leik-the-timeless-song-composer&format=pdf&option=com_content&Itemid=279 |title= Sai Kham Leik : The Timeless Song Composer |author=Sai Wansai |date=21 April 2009 |publisher=Shanland.org |accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref> He is vital composer of late [[Sai Htee Saing]], a well-known Shan singer of Myanmar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myanmaronlinemusic.com/ |title=Myanmar Online Mp3 Songs |publisher=Myanmar Online Music |date= |accessdate=2013-08-20}}</ref> They met in 1969 and later they founded a music band which became a successful '''The Wild Ones'''.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130202130246/http://www.shanmp3.com/index.php/2012-04-09-11-30-38/209-biography-of-sai-htee-seng ]</ref> "[[Panglong Agreement]]" is his most cerebrated song among Shan since 1971. It was sung by Sai Hsai Mao and recorded in [[Thailand]] in 1974 with the financial support of a renounced [[Va people|Wa]] leader.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.english.panglong.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5103:songwriter-panglong-agreement-inspired-by-cartoon&catid=93:general&Itemid=291 |title=Songwriter: ‘Panglong Agreement’ inspired by cartoon |publisher=English.panglong.org |date=2012-11-28 |accessdate=2013-08-20}}</ref>
